<TEXT>
capitol hill is awash in proposals to tinker 
with who pays what for medicares new catastrophicillness 
insurance program as legislators try to appease outraged senior 
citizens who feel they were stuck with a good idea gone bad 
at issue is the medicare catastrophic coverage act enacted with 
great fanfare last july and touted as bringing peace of mind to 
millions of elderly americans who no longer need fear their life 
savings will be wiped out by staggering medical bills 
in a sunny rose garden ceremony thenpresident reagan and 
congressional architects of the plan hailed its innovative 
financing mechanism which requires those who benefit from the 
program to shoulder all of its costs 
a 15 percent surtax on federal income tax liabilities over 150 
affects about 40 percent of those 65 and older with the maximum 
payment capped at 800 in 1989 and rising to 1050 by 1993 most 
of the rest of the money comes from a flat supplemental premium on 
all but the poorest beneficiaries set at 4 a month in 1989 and 
rising to 1020 by 1993 
thats where the problems began and the peace of mind ended 
some older americans who lobbied hard for the benefits but 
didnt want to foot the bill alone have bombarded congress with 
complaints that their payments are too high and benefits too low 
they also argue that the program should not be mandatory because 
some people already have duplicate private coverage 
since almost all of us one day hope to benefit from the 
medicare program society has a basic responsibility to assist in 
its financing said lawrence smedley executive director of the 
national council of senior citizens 
spurred into action by the rebellion legislators have 
introduced a host of proposals to amend delay or repeal the 
program 
douglas besharov a resident scholar at the american enterprise 
institute said members of congress are trying to satisfy 
everyone or at least everyone who votes in large numbers 
everyone knew this program was going to be very expensive but 
they said dont worry its going to be selffinancing 
besharov said it turns out the deal may not be that binding 
in recent legislative action the house ways and means committee 
last week produced a plan that would halve the income tax 
surcharge increase the supplemental medicare premium paid by all 
but the poorest and limit the prescription drug benefit 
in addition senior citizens could opt out of the catastrophic 
program altogether if they also dropped part b of medicare which 
covers doctor bills and is financed primarily by general tax 
revenue 
the proposal squeezed through on a 1917 vote with proponents 
claiming it would ease the burden on elderly people in the middle 
class allow discontented seniors to drop out and preserve 
valuable benefits for the majority of older americans 
but the plan likely to be a focal point for further debate on 
the future of catastrophic coverage is quickly attracting critics 
among the very constituency it was designed to mollify 
we could never support this said frances humphreys 
executive director of the gray panthers we want to see a better 
financing plan by all means but we dont want to undermine the 
medicare program and we dont want to place any more of a burden on 
the poor 
ken hoagland of the national committee to preserve social 
security and medicare which has been leading the fight against the 
surtax said theyre still leaving the financing on senior 
citizens thats the problem 
sen john mccain rariz called it reprehensible to shift 
more of the costs to lowincome elderly and to portray the revised 
program as voluntary when few people can afford to give up part b 
of medicare a prerequisite for dropping catastrophic insurance 
on a 5840 procedural vote thursday the senate rejected a 
proposal by mccain that would delay implementation of the surtax 
and most of the benefits for a year giving congress time to 
rethink the whole package 
one of the few friendly reviews of the ways and means package 
came from the american association of retired persons which 
expressed concern about the added burden for lowincome 
beneficiaries but called the overall plan a positive step toward 
addressing some of the concerns which have been raised 
john rother aarps legislative director said the main 
alternative to the committees proposal appears to be outright 
repeal which would be far more regressive 
he said that while much of the opposition to the current program 
comes from highincome older americans who would pay the most part 
is from less affluent people who are under the mistaken impression 
they would have to pay the maximum surtax 
in fact less than 6 percent of elderly americans will pay the 
maximum amount 
this program is a great deal at a minimum for 75 percent of 
older people rother said they receive much more in benefits 
than they are asked to pay 
several other senior citizen groups have lined up behind 
legislation that would repeal the surtax retain all the 
catastrophic benefits and replace the lost revenues by extending 
the 33 percent income tax to all earnings of the nations 
highestincome taxpayers some of which now is taxed at 28 percent 
it offers real tax relief to older americans by closing a 
loophole for wealthy taxpayers said sen tom harkin diowa a 
sponsor of that proposal 
</TEXT>
