<TEXT>
a us court of appeals ruling that national 
security archive qualifies as a media organization enables the 
research group to receive discount rates for its numerous requests 
for government documents under the freedom of information act 
the decision friday stemmed from a lawsuit the national security 
archive a nonprofit group that compiles documents on national 
security and foreign policies brought against the defense 
department for its refusal to classify the organization as an 
educational institution or a representative of the news media 
either category would mean the group would not have to pay 
certain searchandreview charges for freedom of information 
act requests a potentially substantial benefit searchand review 
fees at the state department for example vary from 8 an hour to 
30 an hour 
circuit judge douglas h ginsburg writing the unanimous 
decision for the threemember panel said national security archive 
was entitled to media status because it planned to act in 
essence as a publisher for books such as its chronology of the 
irancontra affair and a 1000page index of documents about us 
involvement in el salvador 
</TEXT>
