<TEXT>
william lucas is making little headway in 
winning support from civil rights leaders and black americans in 
his quest for confirmation as the nations chief civil rights 
enforcer 
youre not likely to see a groundswell of black people coming 
out for mr lucas says althea simmons director and chief 
lobbyist of the national association for the advancement of colored 
people 
all but a smattering of civil rights leaders oppose lucas or 
have withdrawn early support as the senate judiciary committee 
nears a vote tuesday on the black former sheriff who switched 
parties in 1986 and became the republican candidate for governor of 
michigan 
the bush administration can probably count on seven of the eight 
votes needed for a favorable recommendation from the committee 
tuesday 
and sen howell heflin dala still undeclared appears able 
to send the 61yearold lucas to the senate floor with the panels 
blessing 
even if the committee rebuffs lucas the fight is likely to 
reach the floor in the long run and be settled by the full senate 
as the showdown nears lucas stands less at odds with the civil 
rights community than the posts last occupant william bradford 
reynolds but that is about the best that can be said of the 
relationship 
that represents a change because civil rights forces initially 
appeared divided over the nomination 
an early supporter rep john conyers dmich introduced lucas 
before the committee two weeks ago and then returned the next day 
to withdraw it saying he was dismayed by the nominees answers to 
questions from the panel 
the rev jesse jackson also withdrew his early support and is 
now among the lucas detractors 
both defections came after a judiciary hearing july 19 at which 
lucas said it was too early to assess the impact of recent supreme 
court decisions limiting the scope of laws to combat job bias and 
establish minority setasides in public works projects 
at the session he appeared uncertain about such matters as the 
difference between de jure segregation that is based in law and 
de facto segregation that exists without any legal basis 
naacp lobbyist simmons said her group was inundated by calls 
from black viewers around the country who had seen the hearing via 
the cablesatellite public affairs network cspan and were 
unimpressed by lucas 
civil rights leaders have narrowed their attack to one point 
they say he simply lacks the experience to do the job he has never 
tried a case filed a brief or handled an appeal 
its as if i had a medical degree but didnt practice medicine 
and were named to head a team of brain surgeons elaine jones of 
the naacp legal defense and educational fund told the committee 
they say attacking lucas on his lack of experience is far 
preferable to following the lead of judiciary committee democrats 
who have questions about the nominees passion for the cause of 
civil rights 
passion is a different thing to different people naacp 
lobbyist simmons said later it is the kind of thing that is not 
quantifiable how do you know he lacks passion but you do know 
that he has never tried a case 
lucas has received backing from a handful of civil rights 
activists around the country as well as black law enforcement 
officials 
among well known civil rights leaders though only the rev 
joseph lowery of the southern christian leadership conference has 
rallied to lucas 
this is not the place to throw down the gauntlet with mr 
bush lowery said it is not a lifetime appointment it is not 
the place were we have gotten our civil rights we have gotten our 
civil rights in the streets and in the supreme court and in the 
congress 
