<TEXT>
a federal agency judge says a victoria texas 
obstetrician let his fear of a malpractice lawsuit cloud his 
judgment when the doctor ordered a poor sick woman who was about 
to give birth transferred to another hospital 160 miles away 
dr michael l burditt the first physician prosecuted for 
violating a 1986 federal law against patient dumping is expected 
to fight the 20000 civil penalty imposed upon him by the 
department of health and human services 
the agency on sunday released the 44page ruling by 
administrative law judge charles e stratton upholding the hhs 
inspector generals sanctions against burditt but reducing the 
fine from 25000 to 20000 
the texas medical association the state branch of the american 
medical association has previously agreed to pay burditts legal 
costs and any fine stemming from his controversial handling of the 
case of rosa rivera 
mrs rivera showed up at the emergency room of detar hospital in 
victoria on dec 5 1986 to have her sixth child without seeing a 
doctor during the pregnancy and with blood pressure of 210 over 160 
high enough to cause stroke and death 
burditt then chief of the hospitals obstetrical department 
was summoned by phone to treat the indigent woman because he was 
next on a list to handle emergency obstetrical calls he told a 
nurse he did not want to take care of this lady and said she 
should be transferred to a better equipped hospital in galveston 
burditt drove in examined her and ordered the transfer to 
proceed despite the objections of nurses worried that it would 
violate the thennew law against patient dumping that law 
specifies that hospitals must treat patients in medical emergencies 
or in active labor 
burditt said he would choose his patients until detar a private 
hospital paid his malpractice premiums but he also stayed to 
deliver a baby of another poor uninsured women who was seven 
months pregnant and bleeding 
mrs rivera in tears was eventually transferred and bore a 
healthy 6pound baby boy in the ambulance parked on the roadside 40 
miles east of victoria she and the baby were returned to detar 
where another doctor treated them 
stratton wrote that the 1986 law was enacted to close the door 
on the shameful practice of denying emergency hospital care to 
many persons in dire need he cited an estimate at a 
congressional hearing that as many as 200000 persons were denied 
emergency hospital care each year primarily for economic reasons 
it is a tragedy that dr burditt a wellrespected physician 
a decent personable man with loyal friends and patients let his 
parochial interests and personal feelings interfere with his 
exercise of sound professional medical judgment stratton said 
burditt testified in january that he had sought to avoid 
highrisk patients in part because of his need to keep regular 
hours as the sole parent of a teenage daughter 
while he never meant to harm mrs rivera he further 
compounded his initial recklessness in ordering her transfer by 
allowing his anger at having his authority challenged by nurses 
to close his mind to the merit of cancelling the transfer 
stratton said 
his unyielding attitude did not prompt him to investigate 
the nurses concerns treat mrs rivera before she was transferred 
or treat mrs rivera when she was returned to detar hospital 
stratton said in this instance although dr burditt was not 
venal he lost sight of his oath as a physician 
the benefits of the transfer depended on two fragile 
individuals surviving a 160170 mile ride bereft of treatment 
said stratton he acted in reckless disregard and deliberate 
ignorance of the law 
stratton said there were both aggravating and mitigating 
circumstances in the case among the former he said were 
burditts failure to consult another doctor in the hospital and his 
refusal to treat her after she had the baby 
the mitigating factors included mrs riveras own failure to get 
prenatal care and the hospitals lack of medical records in her 
case another mitigating factor stratton said was burditts 
subsequent role in creating a new prenatal clinic for poor women in 
victoria and helping improve transfer procedures for sick patients 
in the small city between houston and corpus christi 
detar which nearly lost its eligibility for medicare funding 
paid a 5000 fine after an investigation by the dallas regional 
office of the department of health and human services 
donald p wilcox attorney for the texas medical association on 
saturday called strattons ruling disturbing 
we thought what he did was defensible and accepted practice 
wilcox said 
</TEXT>
