something was missing at father edward 
flanagans famed home for boys 
a city without girls is like a hug without a kiss its good 
but its not enough said the rev val peter executive director 
of boys town 
so 10 years ago the first five girls came to the 1300acre 
campus on the western edge of omaha now 76 women count themselves 
among the more than 17000 alumni of flanagans home for troubled 
and abandoned youth 
about 400 of those alumni participated in a threeday reunion 
that ended sunday 
boys town provides care in a fosterhome setting to troubled 
children sent by courts social service agencies and churches and 
to a few children who arrive there on their own 
of the 526 current boys town residents 201 are girls aged 9 to 
17 peter said 
the transition was not always easy for the first groups of girls 
entering the village founded on flanagans belief that theres no 
such thing as a bad boy 
although she was not among the first five girls to arrive at 
boys town joni renken was one of the first five girls to graduate 
from boys towns high school in 1983 she remembers boys faces 
pressed against the windows in classroom doors as some of the 
pioneer girls entered the school 
it was weird because they were looking around at us and 
running into stuff she said saturday you were like so 
outnumbered 
there was little flirting between the boys and girls said 1987 
boys town graduate traci schacht 
more or less they treated me like a sister she said 
the addition of girls challenged a staff used to dealing only 
with boys peter said the gym teacher was not an early convert 
said mrs renken of lincoln who lived at boys town for one full 
school year and parts of two others 
gym class was one of the worst things because they treated us 
like boys and they worked us like dogs she said 
society was unaware of a problem with wayward girls when 
flanagan founded the home in 1917 or even when mickey rooney 
visited in 1938 for the filming of the famed movie boys town 
peter said 
an awareness of the need to reach out to troubled girls grew he 
said but the first five came by accident in 1979 for shelter 
they didnt have any place to go then we liked them so much 
we said they could stay and weve been taking them ever since 
peter said 
some of the boys that had been here a long time i think 
were kind of resentful that the girls were intruding on their 
space mrs renken said 
then they were really accepting overall i guess they had a 
change of heart it was like a brothersister relationship 
that is exactly the relationship peter hopes to foster 
i hold the capacity for friendship between a boy and a girl to 
be the key to all success in marriage and family if we cant be 
friends all the rest of it isnt going to hold us together 
there is a continuing debate about how many girls to enroll 
peter said 
the boys are warmly recommending we take more girls and the 
girls are warmly recommending that we not take any more girls they 
like the ratio just as it is he said 
mrs renken said the ratio was about one girl per 100 boys when 
she lived at boys town 
we liked the ratio when we were here too 
