britain said sunday it will resume talks with 
china in september over the future of hong kong a british colony 
the talks will be the first formal contact between china and 
britain since the violent military crackdown in june on chinas 
prodemocracy movement 
plans for resuming talks were announced following a meeting 
between foreign secretary john major and foreign minister qian 
qichen of china in paris both are in paris for an international 
peace conference on cambodia 
a foreign office spokesman in london said major and qian agreed 
that a joint liaison group working out details of procedures for 
handing the colony over to china in 1997 will meet in london at the 
end of september and again before the end of the year 
many of hong kongs 57 million inhabitants have become 
increasingly fearful about their future since china began its 
crackdown on dissent 
some hong kong politicians have accused britain of abandoning 
the people of hong kong by refusing to grant automatic residence 
rights to the 3 million british passport holders in the colony 
under a 1984 chinesebritish agreement hong kong is to retain 
its capitalist economy for 50 years 
major said after sundays meeting for the time being the 
chinese foreign minister is in no doubt about our concern about the 
need to restore confidence in hong kong 
