federal racketeering charges stemming from the killing of a police 
officer in 1986 
frederico giovanelli 56 steven maltese 57 and carmine 
gualtiere 55 were found guilty of violating the federal 
racketeering statute loansharking interstate travel in aid of a 
racketeering enterprise and attempted murder 
the verdict came on the fifth day of deliberations following an 
11week trial the defendants were remanded to the metropolitan 
correctional center 
the three men are associated with the genovese crime family 
said us attorney benito romano 
gualtiere was described as a soldier who ran a huge gambling 
business that brought in hundreds of thousands dollars in revenue 
to him and the genovese family prosecutors said 
detective anthony venditti member of an organized crime task 
force was shot to death outside a diner in the ridgewood district 
of queens on jan 21 1986 during mob surveillance his partner 
kathleen burke was wounded when she tried to assist venditti 
romano said the defendants did not know venditti was a police 
officer and were afraid they were going to be ripped off 
gualtiere was acquitted of murder charges in state court in 
april 1988 the jury deadlocked in the case of the two others and a 
mistrial was declared the second in the case 
questions arose as to whether sundays conviction would 
interfere with the states effort to reprosecute the defendants on 
homicide charges due to the double jeopardy law romano said that 
would be decided by the state courts 
giovanelli faces up to 70 years in prison maltese faces 75 
years and gualtiere faces 50 years each could be fined in excess 
of 1 million sentencing was scheduled for oct 18 romano said 
