<TEXT>
frances woodworth wright a harvard 
university astronomer who taught celestial navigation to us navy 
officers died sunday of cancer she was 92 
during more than half a century of research and teaching 
wrights studies ranged from investigating specks of cosmic dust 
called spherules to calculating the brightness of galaxies and 
developing systematic efforts to observe comets and meteors 
but her special interest was celestial navigation the guiding 
of ships by the position of stars among her students were us 
army engineers and navy officers enrolled in special courses during 
world war ii she also taught scores of harvard undergraduates and 
weekend sailors and she wrote three books on sailing by the stars 
many of her students remained fanatically devoted to her 
sending her accounts of survivals and rescues achieved by her 
techniques and gathering in cambridge for an annual reunion to swap 
sea tales said james cornell spokesman for the 
harvardsmithsonian center for astrophysics 
born in providence ri wright attended the moses brown school 
there and earned a bachelors degree from pembroke college in 1919 
and a masters degree from brown university in 1920 she taught 
astronomy and mathematics at elmira college in new york before 
going to harvard in 1928 to serve as an assistant to a succession 
of prominent astronomers including cecilia paynegaposchkin 
harlow shapley and fred whipple 
at the same time she pursued her own studies and earned a 
doctorate in astronomy from radcliffe college in 1958 nearly 50 
years after receiving her undergraduate degree in 1959 she joined 
the staff of the harvard college observatory after retiring in 
1971 she became a lecturer on navigation at harvard and continued 
to teach and do research until two years ago 
her memoirs constant vigilance were published in 1987 
wright who lived in cambridge and never married leaves no 
immediate survivors funeral services will be private 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

